The paper discusses a method for strengthening the abstract transition relation in software model checking, which is a topic related to logic and formal methods (cs.LO). The method involves using interpolants, which are commonly used in program verification and synthesis (cs.PL). The paper also addresses the issue of failure to prove a property, which is a common problem in software engineering (cs.SE). The use of weak approximation and the need for an adequate set of predicates suggest a connection to formal languages and automata theory (cs.FL). Finally, the empirical evaluation of the method suggests a connection to machine learning and data analysis (cs.LG).
